explanation:
For determining whether any operations in OS_BinSemFlush are dead code you must know whether the calls and assignments actually affect program behaviour (i.e. have side effects) and whether the conditional is meaningful. Each listed symbol is required for that analysis:

- OS_ObjectIdGetById: The direct call in OS_BinSemFlush; must know its observable side effects (state changes, locks, transactions) and whether its removal would change behaviour.
- OS_ObjectIdTransactionInit: Used by OS_ObjectIdGetById to start transactions/locking. Needed to determine side effects performed as part of the ObjectId lookup.
- OS_ObjectIdToArrayIndex: Used by OS_ObjectIdGetById to map IDs to internal storage; may read/validate global state — relevant to side effects and whether the call is doing more than a pure query.
- OS_ObjectIdConvertToken: Used by OS_ObjectIdGetById to populate/convert the token returned to the caller; needed to know whether the token carries state or triggers actions.
- OS_ObjectIdTransactionCancel: Used by OS_ObjectIdGetById to rollback/cleanup on errors; relevant to side effects and whether the call performs cleanup actions even on failure.
- OS_BinSemFlush_Impl: The second call inside the conditional; its behaviour and side effects determine if the conditional body is necessary and whether its removal would change behaviour.
- OS_ObjectIndexFromToken: Used by OS_BinSemFlush_Impl to map the token to an internal semaphore object index; may access/modify global object tables — needed to assess side effects.
- OS_Posix_BinSemAcquireMutex: Used by OS_BinSemFlush_Impl (per call graph) — likely performs locking or interaction with underlying POSIX semaphores; needed to know runtime effects/timing consequences.
- OS_LOCK_MODE_NONE: The constant passed to OS_ObjectIdGetById; required to know the lock mode semantics and whether the call performs locking or other operations depending on this value.
- LOCAL_OBJID_TYPE: The object-type constant passed to OS_ObjectIdGetById; affects lookup behaviour (which object table is accessed) and thus potential side effects.
- OS_SUCCESS: The value compared against return_code to decide whether to call OS_BinSemFlush_Impl; required to understand when the conditional branch is taken and whether the assignment/call is reachable/necessary.
- OS_object_token_t: The token type returned via &token; needed to know whether construction/population of the token has side effects or represents initialization (which is not dead code) and whether it is used later.
- osal_id_t: The parameter type of sem_id; understanding its representation can be necessary to know if passing it causes conversions or validations with side effects.

Together these symbols let an analyst determine whether the calls/assignments in OS_BinSemFlush have observable effects (state changes, locks, timing) such that removing them would alter program behaviour (i.e. they are not dead code).
